350003	194	2020-09-29 11:21:42	Lab Development: Lab development is partially completed. \r\na.   Table top required to carry out project experimentation of power combining of two magnetrons has been procured and installed.\r\nb.   Installation of ESD mats, earthing points and power sockets is in progress.\r\n\r\n2.   Magnetron Injection Locking Modeling and Simulation\r\na.   Preliminary injection locking numerical scheme as designed has been investigated using computational modeling. Promising results are achieved in lines with the design.\r\nb.   Various combinations of gain and bandwidth of the injection signal were tested in simulation. The trend was observed to follow the classical Adlers Equation and theory. This analysis has furnished the requirement to develop additional feedback loop to control the characteristics of injection locking signals spectral bandwidth and gain, through FPGA based control circuitry. \r\nc.   Noisy excitation signal to the magnetron was also simulated to investigate the effect on magnetron jittering. Magnetron output was observed to be highly non-stationary (the frequency is varying with respect to time). As mentioned above, this analysis has furnished the requirement to develop additional feedback loops for a stabilized fully controllable power supply through Spartan Xilinx based COTs FPGA.\r\n\r\n3.   RF Devices: Indigenous design and fabrication of following high frequency RF devices are being undertaken to accomplish project experimentation in the given funds. Circulators and couplers required for the experimentation has been modeled and simulated successfully. The production drawings have also been generated. Procurement of raw material is in progress. It is pertinent to mention that limited funds (Rs. 80M) have been allocated against the approved amount (Rs. 146M). The in-house design and development of RF devices will enable completion of project in available funds. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n4.   RF Power Amplifier:\r\n\r\na.   8Wa PA. In-house design and manufacturing of Heat Sink along with packaging of amplifier has been completed. The assembly has been successfully tested on VNA and spectrum analyzer. The thermal performance of PA with the developed sink is also satisfactory.\r\n\r\nb.   100 Watt PA.\r\n1)   In-house design of 100W power amplifier has been completed. Optimization of results through different simulations is in progress.\r\n2)   The raw material for 100W amplifier has been procured. \r\n3)   RLC meter procurement for measurement of RLC components is being undertaken. This will enable optimization and fine tuning of matching circuits used in power amplifiers.\r\n\r\n6.   Control System Designing: As mentioned above, injection locking simulation studies have revealed that sophisticated control loops are required to furnish stable phase and frequency at magnetron output port. Therefore, following control loops are being studied and under development:\r\na.   Feedback loop to furnish control power supply voltage through magnetron pushing characteristics. \r\nb.   Feedback loop to furnish efficient magnetron locking bandwidth by adjusting the bandwidth and gain of the injection signal. \r\nc.   The abovementioned feedback loops will be programmed in above mentioned FPGA. The HR is being trained in the area of control implementation on board FPGAs. \r\n\r\n7.   Hardware Procurement: Project experimentation based on injection locking experimentation of a single magnetron will first be carried out to validate simulated results.\r\na.   Procurement of experimental components including coaxial circulators, coaxial terminations, waveguide transitions, waveguide adapters, power supplies and FPGA boards is in process. \r\nb.   Electronics systems required for injection locking of single magnetron including Phase Locked Loop (PLL) based ICs and Pulse Width Modulation (PWM) ICs are also being procured.\r\n\r\n8.   Anechoic Chamber. Preliminary study on in-house development of anechoic chamber