350015	708	2022-05-11 23:05:38	1.   Following activities pertaining to in-house development and experimentation were carried out:\r\n\r\na.   Small Scale Weapon Field Testing. Preliminary Field testing was of 2.5 KW setup was conducted at RDS NATHIAGALI vide reference PN/NRDI/R AND D WING/03/12427313 dated 16 Feb 22. The interference was observed with drone as target. Multiple targets such as Low Noise Amplifiers (LNAs), Phase Frequency Detectors (PFDs), RF rectifiers and RF Power Meters are being evaluated for disruptive demonstration. Field testing is scheduled to be conducted in early May 2022.\r\n\r\nb.   Horn Antenna Improvement. Horn antenna has been redesigned and fabricated resulting in better efficiency.  A testing was carried out at SPF with one horn antenna used for transmission, and another used for reception. A 47 dBm signal was transmitted at 2.45 GHz, and 13 dBm was received at reception antenna at 10 m, resulting in propagation loss of 34 dB. The exercise was aimed to simulate the in-band damage effect on a missile seeker. The 13 dBm signal is disruptive for LNAs and PFDs used in RADAR systems of missile seekers. Point recommended to be dropped.\r\n\r\nc.   X-Band Experiment. RF devices are being designed and fabricated at X-band for use in power combination of pulsed M1475A 25 kW magnetrons. Power supplies and pulse modulators were procured and have undergone preliminary testing to ensure desired voltages are achieved at pertinent test points. The modulators will now be tested with X-band magnetrons.\r\n\r\n2.   RF Power Amplifier. Biasing circuit PCB has been redesigned with adequate track width suitable for high drain current. The Matching networks of the 100 Watt amplifier have been redesigned employing Simplified Real Frequency Technique (SRFT) for output MN and Bounded Performance Technique (BPT) for input MN. PCB fabrication has been completed; PCB component population is in progress and will available for testing in May 22.\r\n\r\n \r\n3.   Following studies are being conducted to formulate research plans for combination of X-band magnetrons for more effective DEW design: \r\n\r\na.   A pulsed power supply based on Pulsed Forming Networks (PFN) required to drive pulsed magnetrons is currently being designed in-house.\r\n\r\nb.   Preliminary design of RF devices including circulators and directional couplers at X-band (9 GHz) has been finalized. RF devices are under fabrication and testing stages.\r\n\r\n4.   Technical proposal amounting PKR 232M for Phase II pertaining to power combination of multiple J-band pulsed magnetrons of redundant AM-39 has been submitted to NHQ for approval. An anechoic RF chamber will also be designed and fabricated to enable shielded high-power testing of the magnetron combination experiment with adequate safety measures. Point recommended to be dropped.\r\n\r\n5.   The proposal for future plan was also submitted vide Ref no PN/DGNRDI/RNDWING/03/11409776 dated 21ST Nov 21 in which Power Combination of multiple 25Kw pulsed J-band magnetrons, to achieve 150 kW combined power, is to be undertaken. Following are the salient highlights of the approach. Point recommended to be dropped.\r\n\r\na.   Pulsed operation philosophy will yield lower operational cost, lesser cooling requirement, higher lethality compared to CW.\r\n\r\nb.   J-band RF devices will be smaller in size and can be efficiently tailored for installation onboard naval platform.\r\n\r\n6.   Scan Eagle. INTELL NRDI RF team visited PNS MAKRAN to conduct defect diagnosis in the RF end of Scan Eagle GCS AIM and Directional Antenna. \r\n\r\na.   Antenna was found to be mechanically deformed and mismatched at S-band.    Defect rectification was attempted on-site and antenna VSWR parameters were significantly improved. INTELL was also approached to design a new antenna based on solid dish, for which the team took all design measurements on-site. The design study for the antenna is currently in progress. \r\n\r\nb.   RF paths of three of the AIMs were also tested at INTELL on VNA. The mechanical filters of two of the systems were found degraded.	DSensors	Finalized	2022-06-04 04:42:50	25	Apr 22	-19-25-	\N	f	\N
