osal for future plan was also submitted vide Ref no PN/DGNRDI/RNDWING/03/11409776 dated 21 Nov 21 in which Power Combination of multiple 25Kw pulsed J-band magnetrons, to achieve 150 kW combined power, is to be undertaken. Following are the salient highlights of the approach. Point recommended to be dropped.\r\n\r\na.   Pulsed operation philosophy will yield lower operational cost, lesser cooling requirement, higher lethality compared to CW.\r\n\r\nb.   J-band RF devices will be smaller in size and can be efficiently tailored for installation onboard naval platform.\r\n\r\n7.   Scan Eagle. INTELL NRDI RF team visited PNS MAKRAN to conduct defect diagnosis in the RF end of Scan Eagle GCS AIM and Directional Antenna. \r\n\r\na.   Antenna was found to be mechanically deformed and mismatched at S-band.    Defect rectification was attempted on-site and antenna VSWR parameters were significantly improved. INTELL was also approached to design a new antenna based on solid dish, for which the team took all design measurements on-site. The design study for the antenna is currently in progress. PPF forms are awaited from NHQ, which once received will help ensure proper utilization of developed HR and computational resources at INTELL. \r\n\r\nb.   RF paths of three of the AIMs were also tested at INTELL on VNA. The mechanical filters of two of the systems were found degraded. PPF form for development of these filters is awaited from NHQ.\r\n\r\n8.   GPS Band stop Filter. PN DY approached NRDI INTELL for GPS deactivation of INMARSAT TT3020-C. INTELL proposed development of an absorptive reflection-less GPS band stop filter to ensure protection of low power elements such as LNAs and MUX in the transceiver circuitry from high power reflection signals. A 3rd order band stop microstrip absorptive filter is designed and is currently under final fabrication stages. Subsequent testing will be conducted on VNA.	DSensors	Finalized	2022-08-02 23:18:48	25	May 22	-19-25-	\N	f	\N
